#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:5
msgid ""
"Here there are some important points for organizing the tutorials for the "
"SciPy conference.  They are based on the experience of previous conferences "
"so please, for the sake of keeping future organizers happier, you are "
"encouraged update this document in the parts that are necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:13
msgid "Decision points"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:16
msgid "Tracks"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:18
msgid ""
"2013 had 3 different tracks (introductory, intermediate and advanced) with 4"
" slots of 4 hours each per track."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:21
msgid ""
"Feedback was positive for this arrangement both years, and we fairly easily "
"filled 60-80 slots per tutorial."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:23
msgid "More details are in `mailings/tutorials_announcement.rst`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:25
msgid ""
"2014 had 4 different tracks (introductory, intermediate, advanced, topics) "
"with 4 slots of 4 hours each per track."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:28
msgid ""
"2015 had 5 different tracks: 1 full 2 day track for Software Carpentry and 4"
"  tracks (Basics, Statistics and Machine Learning, Performance and "
"Optimization, and Special Topics), which each specified a knowledge level "
"for the individual tutorial as beginner, intermediate, or advanced, with 4 "
"slots of 4 hours each per track. Machine Learning (2 connected tutorials) "
"was so popular we actually had a 6th tutorial track on day 2 to repeat the "
"tutorial from day 1."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:31
msgid "Seating"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:33
msgid ""
"Before 2013, we had open seating (i.e. anybody can go to any tutorial). In "
"2013 and 2014, we required people to sign up to attend the tutorial they "
"were interested in, and in both years several tutorials were full."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:37
msgid ""
"In 2013, we had people at the door of full tutorials checking names as folks"
" entered. This was effective, but a bit annoying."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:40
msgid ""
"In 2014, most of the tutorials were either full or close to full. Even "
"\"full\" tutorials had capacity for an extra ~10 people. We did not check "
"names at the door, and there were no complaints about lack of seating."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:44
msgid ""
"In 2015, most tutorials were either full or close to full, even with more "
"tracks. Rooms ranged in size from about 60 to about 95 max and some space "
"was left for volunteers and people to step in."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:47
#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:97
msgid "Introductory Track"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:49
msgid ""
"There are two approaches to the introductory track: a single, coherent "
"curriculum, or a mishmash of multiple intro-level tutorials. In 2013-2014, "
"we found we needed to solicit intro tutorials from the community."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:53
msgid ""
"In 2013, the committee chose specific people from the community and asked "
"them to submit intro tutorials. There were more submissions than spaces "
"available, and this led to a nice selection of intro topics."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:57
msgid ""
"In 2014, we make a general solicitation when the proposal due-date was "
"extended, and this led to a good selection of intro-level submissions."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:60
msgid ""
"In the early days of SciPy, there was a single tutorial track which served "
"as a broad intro to scientific computing in Python. In years since we've "
"moved away from that, but there was some discussion around whether it would "
"be good to return to a multiday, coherent tutorial for beginners."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:65
msgid ""
"One idea for this would be to outsource to Software Carpentry, but it's not "
"clear that Greg Wilson would support doing this. Another option is to "
"specifically solicit intro proposals from a group of 3-4 people who are "
"willing to work together and do a 2-day intro track from the ground up. With"
" this, the intro track would look a lot more like the original scipy "
"conference tutorials."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:72
msgid ""
"In any case, we need to make sure that the intro sections are taught by "
"someone who has experience in getting people started from the ground-up: "
"i.e. you can't just say \"pull this from github\" or \"run Python from the "
"command-line\": the students may not know what \"github\" and the \"command "
"line\" are!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:78
msgid ""
"In 2015 we did have a Software Carpentry track for 2 days to try to reach "
"out to people who are truly new. This worked pretty well: there were reports"
" of fewer newbies in the lower level tutorials and the SC tutorial went "
"well, but it wasn't very well attended. We think this is still a good idea, "
"but needs to be advertised better and to be possibly broken into 4 hour "
"chunks like the other tutorials instead of keeping people in the track the "
"whole time."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:82
msgid "Tracks and call for proposals"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:84
msgid ""
"It is a pre-condition to have the tracks nailed down before the call for "
"submissions announcement.  In 2013, 3 different tracks (introductory, "
"intermediate and advanced) were scheduled, and we decided to have 4 slots of"
" 4 hours each per track. In 2014, we had four different tracks "
"(introductory, intermediate, advanced, topical). More details can be seen in"
" `mailings/tutorials_announcement.rst`"
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:91
msgid ""
"In 2014 and especially 2015, we really chose the tracks based on the "
"submissions we got."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:93
msgid ""
"Require that people will have their materials ready a month ahead of time "
"and recommend that they use iPython notebooks to teach with so that the "
"students have the materials to use later and to be able to better follow "
"along."
msgstr ""

#: ../../scipy-conference/manual/committees/tutorials.rst:99
msgid ""
"This is one of the most important in terms of bringing new people into the "
"SciPy community. In 2013, we had to pull the attention of instructors for "
"most of the tutorial submissions in this category.  We will need to "
"encourage submissions and/or invite people to teach these topics. We may "
"want to specify four 1/2 topics and invite proposals for those specific "
"topics."
msgstr ""

